<div id="review_1111912802" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1111912802" />
    <a title="Bob Schnell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16802193-bob-schnell"><img alt="Bob Schnell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359151411p2/16802193.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1111912802?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bob Schnell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bob Schnell" href="/user/show/16802193-bob-schnell">Bob Schnell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16802193-bob-schnell?shelf=read-in-2014">read-in-2014</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16802193-bob-schnell?shelf=general-non-fiction">general-non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1111912802" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10037609030387018890">Advanced reading copy Due to be published February 2015<br/><br/>I read the psychology classic &quot;The Fifty-Minute Hour&quot; by Dr. Robert M. Lindner over 30 years ago and some of the stories within have stayed with me. The chance to read another non-fiction collection of psychotherapy tales led me to pick Irving Yalom&apos;s &quot;Creatures of a Day&quot; off the ARC shelf at work.<br/><br/>Dr. Yalom has written a number of books dealing with psychotherapy and philosophy, none of which I have read. In this book he is obviously dealing</span>
  <span id="freeText10037609030387018890" style="display:none">Advanced reading copy Due to be published February 2015<br /><br />I read the psychology classic "The Fifty-Minute Hour" by Dr. Robert M. Lindner over 30 years ago and some of the stories within have stayed with me. The chance to read another non-fiction collection of psychotherapy tales led me to pick Irving Yalom's "Creatures of a Day" off the ARC shelf at work.<br /><br />Dr. Yalom has written a number of books dealing with psychotherapy and philosophy, none of which I have read. In this book he is obviously dealing with a fair amount of self-reflection at the end of his life and relating his feelings through the stories of some of his patients. Many of the stories deal with death of a loved one, approaching death due to illness, finding one's self and identity late in life, etc. Unfortunately, the end result for this reader was a feeling of depression and low self esteem. This book may have actually triggered a mild mid-life crisis. Although I can find no fault with the writing and I can see how others may gain insight or be entertained, I was left feeling that I needed the author's professional services. To quote the Rolling Stones, "What a drag it is getting old!"</span>
  <a data-text-id="10037609030387018890" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


