<div id="review_1594263671" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1594263671" />
    <a title="Troy Blackford" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4177031-troy-blackford"><img alt="Troy Blackford" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442519986p2/4177031.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1594263671?book_show_action=true">Mar 29, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Troy Blackford" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Troy Blackford" href="/user/show/4177031-troy-blackford">Troy Blackford</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1594263671" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16134478629543830849">This is a measured and clear-headed summation of a few of Dr. Irvin Yalom&apos;s therapy sessions with patients he found particularly notable. I enjoyed this, finding the look at the inner lives of these people to be revealing, and Yalom&apos;s sharing of his thought-process to be enlightening. These cases aren&apos;t the mind-bending, &apos;only three people in history have ever had this diagnosis&apos; nailbiters of cases that you&apos;ll find in a lot of Oliver Sack&apos;s work, and though many of the situations shared here in</span>
  <span id="freeText16134478629543830849" style="display:none">This is a measured and clear-headed summation of a few of Dr. Irvin Yalom's therapy sessions with patients he found particularly notable. I enjoyed this, finding the look at the inner lives of these people to be revealing, and Yalom's sharing of his thought-process to be enlightening. These cases aren't the mind-bending, 'only three people in history have ever had this diagnosis' nailbiters of cases that you'll find in a lot of Oliver Sack's work, and though many of the situations shared here involve profound elements, there is something more universal and in many ways 'simple' about this book. I do not mean simple in a negative way, but in a way that suggests just how cleanly-expressed and applicable to day-to-day life this book is.<br /><br />If you're only ever going to read one book like this, I do not think this should be that book. But if your interest in this topic is deep, this book will reward you with its quiet thoughtfulness and the richness of Yalom's experience.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16134478629543830849" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


