  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3176861060" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3176861060" />
    <a title="Ankit" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3732902-ankit"><img alt="Ankit" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1340961768p2/3732902.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3176861060?book_show_action=true">Apr 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ankit" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ankit" href="/user/show/3732902-ankit">Ankit</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3176861060" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4470122055043175377">Therapists are models of mental strength. Through years of reading Freud and Jung they have managed to overcome their own pedestrian anxieties. At least that&apos;s what their clients believe. Yalom&apos;s stories show otherwise.<br/><br/>For those unfamiliar, Yalom is one of the pioneers of the school of Existential Therapy. Existential Therapists believe that all psychological pain arises from four existential fears: 1. Fear of death 2. Fear of loneliness 3. Fear of freedom and choice and 4. Fear of meaninglessne</span>
  <span id="freeText4470122055043175377" style="display:none">Therapists are models of mental strength. Through years of reading Freud and Jung they have managed to overcome their own pedestrian anxieties. At least that's what their clients believe. Yalom's stories show otherwise.<br /><br />For those unfamiliar, Yalom is one of the pioneers of the school of Existential Therapy. Existential Therapists believe that all psychological pain arises from four existential fears: 1. Fear of death 2. Fear of loneliness 3. Fear of freedom and choice and 4. Fear of meaninglessness. Stories in the book find their origin in one or many of these existential fears.<br /><br />Yalom was over 80 when he wrote this, and his own death anxieties were raising their head. He’s reminded of his age and mortality when he sees his patients: young, old and terminally ill. You sense his death anxieties manifest in various forms in his patients, and the narrative he has constructed to deal with them. Ongoing therapy and studying the still mysterious human mind help him face old age.<br /><br />He humbly admits that he is frequently surprised by how clients manage to resolve their psychological issues. His clients often find solutions to their psychological problems in unexpected places: Yalom's own secretary who helped clean up a client’s apartment, a reading of Marcus Aurelius’ Meditation. Such unfoldings make him question his own subject understanding and the broader underpinnings of therapy. He cautions therapists against boxing their clients into clear identifiable psychiatric problems (like ADHD or mania) with template treatments. This limits both the therapist and the client.<br /><br />He marvels about the complexity of the human mind even as he turns 80. The last story “Creatures of a Day” is an example. The final story that lends it name to the book is derived from a quote in Meditations:<br /><br />“All of us are creatures of a day; the rememberer and the remembered alike. All is ephemeral—both memory and the object of memory. The time is at hand when you will have forgotten everything; and the time is at hand when all will have forgotten you. Always reflect that soon you will be no one, and nowhere.”<br /><br /><i>Creatures of a Day</i> story centers on two of his patients, both tackling different issues: Andrew, who feels stuck in an advertising job and Jarod, who can’t decide if he wants to marry his girlfriend, who has been diagnosed with cancer. Yalom suggests that they read Meditations. To his surprise, both find something different that was useful in what Aurelius had to say.<br /><br />“Take away thy opinion, and then there is taken away the complaint, “I have been harmed.” Take away the complaint, “I have been harmed,” and the harm is taken away.” Give up the victimhood and you’re no longer the victim. The stoic wisdom helps Andrew navigate through his workplace crises and positively approach it, rather than passively observe his own life. While Jarod, who struggles with self esteem issues and has a pathological desire to impress others including Yalom, finds his resonant words in “I have often wondered how it is that every man loves himself more than all the rest of men, but yet sets less value on his own opinions of himself than on the opinions of others”.<br /><br />Maybe that’s what Yalom intends for his readers too. Something they can find useful through him and his patients’ work in their own lives.<br /><br /><br /><i>Creatures of a Day isn’t the first Yalom book you should ideally read. Yalom old (and successful) is not as driven or as analytical as he was in his earlier works like Love’s Executioner. With Creatures of Day though, you read a therapist who’s matured. Yalom acknowledges his humanness when he finds in himself the same fears that his clients expected him to exorcise from them.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="4470122055043175377" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


