        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4309264513" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14413299272121865827">Yet another great book of Dr Yalom with wide spectrum of problems, characters and teraphist&apos;s own obstacles. The story which will stay with me forever is probably the last one describing Jarod - a dermatologist and a narcissist and Andrew - a man who stopped seeing sense of his work and started to have existential problems. Two totally different characters with especially Jarod challenging his therapist and sabotaging every each session to the point that it felt for a doctor that they stuck and </span>
  <span id="freeText14413299272121865827" style="display:none">Yet another great book of Dr Yalom with wide spectrum of problems, characters and teraphist's own obstacles. The story which will stay with me forever is probably the last one describing Jarod - a dermatologist and a narcissist and Andrew - a man who stopped seeing sense of his work and started to have existential problems. Two totally different characters with especially Jarod challenging his therapist and sabotaging every each session to the point that it felt for a doctor that they stuck and no much can help. <br />Ironically what doctor thought will help one patient, did help another and this way of keep trying to establish relationship and be curious about another person is crucial yet unknown even for so experienced therapist like dr Yalom. What I try to say here is that in his books he stresses how important is to not follow any specific school or approach to therapy and simply focus on a person.<br />I found this book very interesting and gave me lots of clues about personal development and the way human brains works. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14413299272121865827" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


